education, and business career==\nJeff Duncan was born in [[Greenville, South Carolina]] on January 7, 1966.<ref name=Kinnard2012/> Duncan's father worked in the textile business and moved the family across the South while Duncan was growing up. After attending three years of high school at Mooresville Senior High School in Mooresville, NC, Duncan moved to [[Ware Shoals, South Carolina|Ware Shoals]] and attended [[Ware Shoals, South Carolina|Ware Shoals High School]]. During his senior year of high school, he met his future wife, Melody Hodges. Duncan graduated [[Clemson University]] in 1988 where he walked on as a [[Wide receiver (American football)|wide receiver]] on the [[Clemson Tigers football|football team]]. His experience as a walk-on player was later the inspiration for the title of his blog, \"Walk-On Legislator,\" which he used to communicate with constituents while serving in the South Carolina General Assembly.\n\nAfter graduation, Duncan served as branch manager and an Assistant Vice President during his seven years of working in community banking. Later, he started his own small business, J. Duncan & Associates, a South Carolina based, family owned real estate marketing firm which specialized in statewide real estate auctions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jeffduncan.house.gov/about-me/full-biography|title=Full Biography {{!}} Congressman Jeff Duncan|website=jeffduncan.house.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref> He ran and operated that business until his election to Congress in 2010.\n\n==South Carolina House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\nDuncan ran for South Carolina's 15th House District in 2002. In the Republican primary, he defeated David Tribble Jr, Clinton county councilman, 56%\u201344%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=42568 |title=SC State House 015 - R Primary Race - Jun 11, 2002 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2017-03-07}}</ref> He won the general election with 62% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=40161 |title=SC State House 015 Race - Nov 05, 2002 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2017-03-07}}</ref> In 2004, he won re-election to a second term unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=41626|title=Our Campaigns - SC State House 015 Race - Nov 02, 2004|website=www.ourcampaigns.com}}</ref> In 2006, he won re-election to a third term with 63% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=168455 |title=SC State House 015 Race - Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2017-03-07}}</ref> In 2008, he won re-election to a fourth term unopposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=451667 |title=SC State House 015 Race - Nov 04, 2008 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2017-03-07}}</ref> In 2010, he retired in order to run for the [[U.S. House of Representatives]]. David Tribble, Duncan's primary opponent in 2002, won Duncan's seat.\n\n===Tenure===\nHe was given the guardian of small business award from the [[National Federation of Independent Businesses]], an A+ rating from the [[Club for Growth]], the Palmetto Leadership Award from the SC policy council, and legislator of the year from the SC Recreation and Parks Association and SC Wildlife Federation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scstatehouse.gov/members/bios/0506818121.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100921145445/http://www.scstatehouse.gov/members/bios/0506818121.html |archivedate=2010-09-21 |df= }}</ref> He was also named a \"Taxpayer's Hero\" by then Governor [[Mark Sanford]] for his work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbr.com/duncan-house-energy-commerce/|title=House E&C Committee Now Runnin' With Duncan {{!}} Radio & Television Business Report|website=www.rbr.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-25}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nDuncan was named chairman of the House Agriculture, Natural Resources and Environmental Affairs Committee, in 2007. He was appointed to Chair of the Education Finance Study and Natural Gas Offshore Drilling Study Committee. He also served as South Carolina's representative on the Southern States Energy Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeffduncan.com/site/about-2/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001000213/http://www.jeffduncan.com/site/about-2/ |archivedate=2010-10-01 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n\n==== 2010 ====\n{{see also|United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina, 2010#District 3}}\nHe ran for [[South Carolina's 3rd congressional district]] when Republican incumbent U.S. representative [[J. Gresham Barrett]] ran for [[governor of South Carolina]]. He was an early Tea Party favorite and was endorsed by the [[Club for Growth]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clubforgrowth.org/endorsedcandidates/?subsec%3D0%26id%3D702 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920035732/http://clubforgrowth.org/endorsedcandidates/?subsec=0&id=702 |archivedate=2010-09-20 |df= }}</ref> and the [[National Right to Life Committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeffduncan.com/site/2010/09/national-right-to-life-endorses-duncan/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-19 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001003151/http://www.jeffduncan.com/site/2010/09/national-right-to-life-endorses-duncan/ |archivedate=2010-10-01 |df= }}</ref> In the Republican primary, businessman Richard Cash ranked first with 25% but failed to reach the 50% threshold to win outright. Duncan ranked second in the six candidate field with 23%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=523030 |title=SC - District 03 - R Primary Race - Jun 08, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2017-03-07}}</ref> In the run-off election, Duncan defeated Cash 51%\u201349%, a vote difference of 2,171. Duncan won five of the district's ten counties, and were mostly located in the southern part of the Congressional District.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=657940 |title=SC District 03 - R Runoff Race - Jun 22, 2010 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2017-03-07}}</ref> He won the general election with 62% of the vote, 2% less than [[John McCain]]'s 64% vote in 2008. He won nine of the district's ten counties, losing just McCormick (52%\u201347%).  Duncan spent $935,503; [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Jane Ballard Dyer]] spent $272,698.<ref name=Barone2012/><ref>{{cite web\n  |accessdate=2013-09-08 |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=511274\n  |title=SC \u2013 District 03 Race |date=Nov 2, 2010 |work=Our Campaigns}}</ref>\n\n==== 2012 ====\n{{see also|United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina, 2012#District 3}}\nDuncan successfully ran for re-election in the newly redrawn 3rd district, which excludes [[Aiken County, South Carolina|Aiken County]] (McCain won with 62%),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aikenstandard.com/story/0901-jeff-duncan|title=U.S.   Rep. Duncan promises to represent Aiken despite congressional redistricting|work=Aiken Standard}}</ref> and includes two new counties: [[Newberry County, South Carolina|Newberry]] (McCain won with 58%) and [[Greenville County, South Carolina|Greenville]] (McCain won with 57%). Duncan won re-election to a second term with 67% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/2012-election/map/#/House/2012/SC|title=2016 Primary Election Results: President Live Map by State, Real-Time Voting Updates|work=Election Hub}}</ref>\n\n==== 2014 ====\nDuncan successfully ran for re-election in 2014, winning with 71.18% of the vote against Democratic candidate Barbara Jo Mullis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enr-scvotes.org/SC/53424/149816/en/summary.html|title=2014 Statewide General Election Results|last=|first=|date=|website=www.enr-scvotes.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-04-11}}</ref>\n\n==== 2016 ====\nDuncan successfully ran for re-election in 2016 with 72.8% of the vote against Democratic candidate Hosea Cleveland. In addition, Duncan was the first Congressional Republican to carry [[McCormick County, South Carolina|McCormick County]] during a Presidential election year. Duncan outperformed Trump by over 5% in 2016.\n\n===Legislation & Tenure===\nDuncan was a \"Tea Party freshman\" in the 112th Congress.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/08/14/debt-stand-by-south-carolina-tea-party-freshmen-hailed-as-heroic|title=Debt Stand by South Carolina Tea Party Freshmen Hailed as Heroic|last=Graham|first=David A.|date=2011-08-15|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn February, 2011, Duncan introduced a resolution to create a new committee on the elimination of nonessential federal programs in an attempt to reduce federal outlays.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeff Duncan Full Biography|url=http://jeffduncan.house.gov/about-me/full-biography|website=U.S. Congressman Jeff Duncan|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2012, Congressman Duncan introduced the Countering Iran in the Western Hemisphere Act of 2012 (H.R. 3783). This bill made it U.S. policy to use a comprehensive strategy to counter Iran's growing hostile presence in the Western Hemisphere by working together with U.S. allies and partners in the region to deter threats to U.S. interest by Iran, the Iranian Islamic Guard Corps (IRGC), the IRGC's Qods Force, and Hezbollah. On December 28, 2012, President Barack Obama signed this into law.\n\nOn November 19, 2012 Duncan wrote a letter to President Obama discouraging him from nominating Ambassador Susan Rice to serve as Secretary of State. Duncan's letter, which was signed by 97 Members of Congress, states that Ambassador Rice \"either willfully or incompetently misled the American public in the Benghazi matter.\" The letter goes on to say that Ambassador Rice has lost the trust of the American people and would greatly undermine the US credibility abroad.\n\nOn April 18, 2013, Duncan introduced the [[Outer Continental Shelf Transboundary Hydrocarbon Agreements Authorization Act]] (H.R. 1613). This bill approved a year-old agreement between the United States and Mexico to allow the joint development of oil and gas straddling the two countries' maritime boundary in the Gulf of Mexico. H.R. 1613 passed the House with bipartisan support on June 27, 2013.  The bill was subsequently wrapped into the Continuing Resolution of December 12, 2013.\n\nOn January 16, 2014 Duncan introduced the Energy Exploration and Production to Achieve National Demand Act (EXPAND Act) (H.R. 3895).  The EXPAND Act renews America's founding principles by freeing Americans to produce more energy in the United States from all sources and contribute to the strength of American national security through North American energy independence.\n\nOn March 13, 2014, Duncan introduced the [[DHS Acquisition Accountability and Efficiency Act (H.R. 4228; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) to improve the accountability, transparency, and efficiency of its major acquisition programs.<ref name=cbo4228>{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 4228|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45385|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=9 June 2014}}</ref> The bill would specify procedures for the department to follow if it fails to meet timelines, cost estimates, or other performance parameters for these programs.<ref name=\"cbo4228\"/><ref name=FTjune10>{{cite news|last1=Medici|first1=Andy|title=House passes bill reforming DHS acquisition management|url=http://www.federaltimes.com/article/20140610/ACQ02/306100013/House-passes-bill-reforming-DHS-acquisition-management?odyssey=nav%7Chead|accessdate=10 June 2014|publisher=Federal Times|date=10 June 2014}}</ref> Duncan argued that \"for years, DHS's purchases of major homeland security systems have been late, cost more, and done less than promised. This bill will save taxpayer dollars by forcing DHS to improve its management.\"<ref name=\"FTjune10\"/>\n\nOn February 23, 2016 Duncan introduced H.Res. 617, which provides the House the authority to file a lawsuit against the Obama Administration should they violate or attempt to violate the law regarding the transfer of detainees from the detention facility at Guantanamo Bay.\n\nIn January 2017 Duncan introduced in the House the Hearing Protection Act of 2017 (HPA) which would reclassify gun [[Suppressor|suppressors (silencers)]] from [[Title II weapons]] to Title I weapons (currently ordinary shotguns, rifles and handguns, weapons \"not regulated by the [[National Firearms Act]], but regulated by the [[Gun Control Act of 1968]] and other federal laws\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Gun Trust Guru: FAQs|url=https://www.guntrustguru.com/faqs|publisher=guntrustguru.com|access-date=October 3, 2017}}</ref>), restricting their regulation and making them easier to buy.<ref name=Newsweek>{{cite web|title=Trump Era Gets Its First Gun Hearing: House to Consider Legislation on Silencers|url=http://www.newsweek.com/house-panel-considers-gun-silencers-legislation-625576|publisher=''[[Newsweek]]''|author=Gorman, Michelle|date=June 14, 2017|access-date=October 3, 2017}}</ref> The HPA amends the [[Internal Revenue Code]] and [[Title 18 of the United States Code]] to eliminate the transfer tax and paperwork associated with registration of suppressors, refund the tax to anyone who paid it after October 22, 2015 (the date the first Hearing Protection Act was introduced, by Rep. [[Matt Salmon]]), and \"preempt\" existing state or local silencer taxes and regulations.<ref>{{cite news|title=House to Vote on Gun Silencer Legislation This Week|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2017-10-02/house-poised-to-pass-law-easing-sale-of-gun-silencers-after-las-vegas-shooting|author=Levy, Gabrielle|publisher=''[[U.S. News & World Report]]''|date=October 2, 2017|access-date=October 3, 2017}} The $200 tax and registration requirements were put into place in 1934 in the [[National Firearms Act|NFA]], when $200 ($3,719.98 in August 2017 dollars) was considered a high enough price to deter Prohibition Era gangsters.\n[https://www.atf.gov/rules-and-regulations/national-firearms-act ATF: National Firearms Act]</ref> In June 2017 Duncan added the HPA to the wide-ranging Sportsmen Heritage and Recreational Enhancement (SHARE) Act, of which he was also the lead sponsor.<ref name=Newsweek/><ref>{{cite news|title=House Committee Passes SHARE Act by Wide Margin|url=https://www.nraila.org/articles/20170915/house-committee-passes-share-act-by-wide-margin|date=September 15, 2017|publisher=[[National Rifle Association]]|access-date=October 3, 2017}}</ref> {{As of|2018|1|30}}, Jeff Duncan has the most conservative [[GovTrack]] ideology score in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/jeff_duncan/412472|title=Jeff Duncan, Representative for South Carolina's 3rd Congressional District \u2013 GovTrack.us|work=GovTrack.us}}</ref>\n\nOn January 19, 2018, Duncan introduced the Ultrasound Informed Consent Act (H.R. 4844) which requires that women seeking an abortion undergo an ultrasound before having an abortion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/4844/|title=H.R.4844 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): Ultrasound Informed Consent Act|last=Jeff|first=Duncan,|date=2018-01-26|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-04-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\nDuncan has received numerous awards during his time in the United States Congress. These awards vary from his views on limited government, conservative voting record, and his support of small businesses.\n\n* Club for Growth's \"Defender of Economic Freedom\" Award<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.clubforgrowth.org/2017-defenders-of-economic-freedom/|title=2017 Defenders of Economic Freedom - Club for Growth|work=Club for Growth|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en-US}}</ref> \n* FreedomWorks \"Freedom Fighter\" Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freedomworks.org/content/freedomworks-announces-freedomfighter-award-winners|title=FreedomWorks Announces FreedomFighter Award Winners {{!}} FreedomWorks|website=www.freedomworks.org|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref>\n* Family Research Council \"True Blue\" Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.frcactionpac.org/election-results|title=FRC Action PAC|website=www.frcactionpac.org|language=en|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref>\n* Act of America \"National Security Patriot Award\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/politics-government/congress/article176821516.html|title=Cruz calls hate group watchdog \u2018leftist institution\u2019 with \u2018sorry record\u2019|work=mcclatchydc|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en}}</ref> \n* NFIB Guardian of Small Business<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wsnwradio.com/congressman-duncan-honored-as-guardian-of-small-business-by-nfib/|title=Congressman Duncan honored as Guardian of Small Business by NFIB  \u2013 94.1 \u2013 The Lake / WSNW|website=wsnwradio.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> \n* Heritage Action \"Sentinel\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizpacreview.com/2013/01/30/heritage-conservative-sentinels-stand-guard-for-freedom-17534|title=Heritage: Conservative 'sentinels' stand guard for freedom|date=2013-01-30|work=Conservative News Today|access-date=2018-05-09|language=en-US}}</ref> \n* 60+ Association \"Guardian of Seniors Rights\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jeffduncan.house.gov/press-release/jeff-duncan-receives-guardian-seniors-rights-award|title=Jeff Duncan Receives Guardian of Seniors' Rights Award {{!}} Congressman Jeff Duncan|website=jeffduncan.house.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref>\n\n===Positions===\nDuncan is pro-life.[http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Jeff_Duncan_Abortion.htm] He has cosponsored legislation to ban late-term abortions, to remove federal funding from abortion providers like Planned Parenthood,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/217|title=H.R.217 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): Title X Abortion Provider Prohibition Act|last=Diane|first=Black,|date=2017-01-25|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> and to protect conscience rights for businesses and healthcare providers who oppose paying for or participating in abortions. He supports [[Gun politics in the United States|gun rights]]. In addition to introducing the Hearing Protection Act, Duncan has cosponsored bills to expand concealed carry reciprocity rights. Duncan is a Lifetime Member of the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]] and has been endorsed by the NRA and given an A rating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/interest-group/581/rating/5600#.Wt_vtojwbIU|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-25}}</ref>\n\nHe voted for the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aikenstandard.com/news/s-c-aiken-republicans-supported-house-tax-bill/article_74d44da2-e4fd-11e7-8251-0f2c11c37827.html|title=S.C., Aiken Republicans supported House tax bill|last=cdemarest@aikenstandard.com|first=Colin Demarest|work=Aiken Standard|access-date=2018-04-25|language=en}}</ref> He also cosponsored legislation to repeal the [[Income tax in the United States|income tax]], the [[Estate tax in the United States|estate tax]], and the entirety of the [[Taxation in the United States|tax code]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/25|title=H.R.25 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): FairTax Act of 2017|last=Rob|first=Woodall,|date=2017-01-03|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref>\n\nDuncan supports federal infrastructure, but believes states should have control over their transportation decisions and this will provide more relief from government regulation.\n\nDuncan supported the full repeal of the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], voting on numerous occasions to repeal it in whole or in part. Duncan supports replacing it with free market solutions, having cosponsored legislation to expand health savings accounts, make all health care spending tax deductible, supporting Christian charity health plans, and creating association health plans.\n\nDuncan opposes a path to citizenship for illegal immigrants. Duncan supports the construction of a border wall with physical fencing, surveillance technology, and increased border patrol agents on the ground. In February 2017, Duncan introduced the Terrorist Deportation Act (H.R. 844),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/844|title=H.R.844 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): Terrorist Deportation Act of 2017|last=Jeff|first=Duncan,|date=2017-03-02|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> which makes it harder for suspected terrorists to come to the United States and remove those who are already here.<ref name=\"Kinnard2012\" /> Duncan is also a cosponsor of \"Goodlatte/McCaul\", H.R. 4760,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-bill/4760|title=H.R.4760 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): Securing America's Future Act of 2018|last=Bob|first=Goodlatte,|date=2018-01-24|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-05-09}}</ref> which requires mandatory E-verify, makes it a crime to overstay a visa, eliminates chain migration, ends the diversity lottery, and creates an agriculture work visa program.\n\nDuncan is a supporter of a free-market, all-of-the-above approach to energy, and has been a champion for both national and hemispheric energy independence. Duncan sponsored the legislation to implement the [[Outer Continental Shelf Transboundary Hydrocarbon Agreements Authorization Act]]. He has also cosponsored legislation supporting offshore energy exploration, seismic testing, clean coal technology, nuclear energy production, and the export of natural gas. Duncan has also worked to ease regulations on [[hydraulic fracturing]], [[coal ash]], the [[Social cost of carbon|Social Cost of Carbon]], and the [[Clean Water Rule]]. Duncan was in favor of the January 2018 decision by the [[United States Department of the Interior|Department of the Interior]] and [[Bureau of Ocean Energy Management]] to allow more access to the [[Outer Continental Shelf]].\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''Committee on Energy and Commerce'''\n** Subcommittee on Digital Commerce and Consumer Protection\n** Subcommittee on Energy\n** Subcommittee on Environment\n* [[Republican Study Committee]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> \n* [[Freedom Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=What is the House Freedom Caucus, and who's in it?|author=|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/10/20/house-freedom-caucus-what-is-it-and-whos-in-it/|format=|publisher=Pew research center|date=20 October 2015|accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nDuncan is married to Melody (Hodges) Duncan, and has three sons. He lives in [[Laurens, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news |date=July 23, 2008 |first=John |last=O'Connor\n |url=http://www.heraldonline.com/2008/07/23/698854/lawmakers-to-tackle-sc-school.html |accessdate=2013-09-08\n |title=Lawmakers to tackle S.C. school funding |newspaper=[[Rock Hill Herald]] Online}}</ref><ref name=\"Kinnard2012\">{{cite news|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/external/pre-election/bios/57891.html?SITE=WSJVTVELN&SECTION=POLITICS&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT|title=News From The Associated Press (Jeff Duncan Candidate Profile)|last=|first=|date=2016-03-04|work=Associated Press|accessdate=2013-09-08|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304053458/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/external/pre-election/bios/57891.html?SITE=WSJVTVELN&SECTION=POLITICS&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT|archivedate=2013-07-07|dead-url=}}</ref><ref name=Barone2012>{{cite book\n  |last=Barone |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Barone (pundit) |author2=Chuck McCutcheon\n  |title=[[The Almanac of American Politics]] 2012 |year=2011 |publisher=[[National Journal Group]] |location=[[Washington, D.C.]]\n  |isbn=978-0-226-03808-7 |pages=1453\u20131455 |lccn=2011929193}}</ref>\n\n==Congressional Baseball Shooting==\n{{Main|2017 Congressional baseball shooting}}\n\nAccording to Duncan, the shooter, James Thomas Hodgkinson, approached him at his car and asked if Democrats or Republicans were on the field. Duncan told reporters later, \"The world changed a little bit today for us as members\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.postandcourier.com/news/shooter-asked-s-c-s-rep-jeff-duncan-if-democrats/article_65b6fe14-50fb-11e7-8159-9fddfc24b1a7.html|title=Shooter asked S.C.'s Rep. Jeff Duncan if 'Democrats or Republicans' were practicing before firing shots|last=edumain@postandcourier.com|first=Emma Dumain|work=Post and Courier|access-date=2018-02-22|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://jeffduncan.house.gov/ Congressman Jeff Duncan] official U.S. House site\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100930235955/http://www.jeffduncan.com/site/ Jeff Duncan for Congress]\n* {{C-SPAN